      "title": "Before and After",
      "text": "'Before 1890,' the woman says, 'a story was a *machine for delivering an outcome*. Edgar Allan Poe said every sentence should drive toward a single preconceived effect. Guy de Maupassant built perfect little traps. O. Henry gave you twist endings like a magician pulling a rabbit from a hat.'\n\nShe sets a fourth manuscript on the table -- older, dog-eared. 'Read the last line of any of those and you knew exactly what the story meant. The writer told you. The ending was a closed door.'\n\n'Then Chekhov came along and *left the door open*. He wrote a story about a married man who has an affair at a seaside resort, and at the end nobody decides anything. The most important line is: *the most complicated and difficult part was only just beginning*. That is not an ending. That is a beginning disguised as an ending.'\n\nShe leans forward. 'Joyce took it further -- prose that does the work of poetry, snow falling on the living and the dead. And Hemingway went the opposite direction: he took everything *out*. One-eighth above the surface, seven-eighths below.'\n\n'Three writers. Three solutions to the same problem: how do you represent the inner lives of people who cannot or will not speak honestly?'\n\nShe pushes the three manuscripts toward Sam.",
