      "text": "Sam puts down the manuscripts. 'I think I get the general idea,' Sam says. 'Plot gave way to consciousness. Chekhov opened the door. Joyce made prose into poetry. Hemingway stripped it bare. I can write that on the exam.'\n\nThe woman looks at Sam for a long moment. 'You can summarize it,' she says. 'That is not the same as understanding it.'\n\nThe bookshelves stop breathing. The room folds up like a closing book. Sam wakes in the campus bookshop. The lights are off. The owner has gone.\n\nSam walks home in the dark, writes a competent exam essay the next morning, and gets a B+. It is a perfectly adequate grade. It is also, Sam suspects, exactly the kind of ending Chekhov would have refused to write -- neat, finished, and fundamentally dishonest about how things actually feel.\n\nThe three paperbacks sit on Sam's desk for years, spines uncracked after that night. Sometimes Sam picks one up and puts it down again.\n\nSome books wait.",
