      "title": "Whose Voice Is This?",
      "text": "Sam listens more carefully. Gurov is watching Anna across a restaurant table. She is telling him about her husband, whom she calls '*a flunkey*.' The narrator reports: '*His wife seemed to him half as long again as he.*'\n\nWait. Is that the narrator's observation, or Gurov's resentful perception of his own wife back in Moscow? It is both at once. The narrator has borrowed Gurov's voice without using quotation marks, without announcing '*Gurov thought*.' The reader is thinking alongside the character without knowing where the boundary is.\n\nThis is *free indirect discourse* -- and Chekhov deploys it like a magician. When Gurov dismisses women as 'the lower race,' is that Chekhov's view? Of course not. But Chekhov never *says* it is wrong. He lets us hear the thought, lets us sit with it, and trusts us to recognize the gap between what Gurov believes about himself and what is actually true.\n\nSam suddenly understands: Chekhov is not telling us what to think. He is creating a window into Gurov's mind and letting us look through it -- biases, self-deceptions, and all. The reading is the judgment.",
