      "title": "The Sea at Oreanda",
      "text": "Night. Sam stands on the cliff at Oreanda while Gurov and Anna sit on a bench nearby, the affair already begun. Below them, the sea makes what Chekhov calls a '*monotonous, hollow sound*' -- and then the narrative lifts, suddenly, into something enormous:\n\n'*The monotonous hollow sound of the sea rising up from below, spoke of the peace, of the eternal sleep awaiting us. So it must have sounded when there was no Yalta, no Oreanda here; so it sounds now, and it will sound as indifferently and monotonously when we are all no more.*'\n\nSam feels the scale shift. A moment ago this was a story about two people having an affair. Now it is about time, mortality, the indifference of the natural world to human feeling. Chekhov has done this in a single paragraph -- opened a trapdoor beneath a love scene and dropped both characters and reader into something vast.\n\nAnna turns to Gurov. '*I wanted to live! To live, to live!*' she says. And the word *live* suddenly carries more weight than it did a page ago, because the sea has just reminded us that living is temporary.\n\nSam realizes: setting in Chekhov is not decoration. It is emotional landscape.",
