      "text": "Sam sees Gurov at the center of two worlds that cannot touch each other.\n\nIn one: the bank, the club, the wife who spells words phonetically, the dinners where people talk about sturgeon. This is the public life -- 'full of conventional truth and conventional deception, exactly like the lives of his friends and acquaintances.'\n\nIn the other: Anna. Secret meetings at the Slaviansky Bazaar hotel in Moscow. Her grey dress. His greying hair. Both older now. Both trapped. Both real.\n\n'*Everything that was essential, of interest and of value to him, everything in which he was sincere and did not deceive himself, everything that made the kernel of his life, was hidden from other people.*'\n\nSam reads that sentence twice. It is the key to the entire story. Gurov's authentic self exists only in secret. His public self is a performance. And the story's quiet argument is that this is not unusual -- that most people live this way, carrying their real selves like contraband.\n\nChekhov does not judge Gurov for the affair. He does not judge Anna for her tears. He does not even judge the colleague and his sturgeon. He simply shows what it looks like when a person's inner life has nowhere to go.",
