      "title": "Only Just Beginning",
      "text": "The final scene. A hotel room. Anna is crying. Gurov looks in the mirror and sees that his hair is grey. '*Only now when his head was grey had he fallen properly, really in love -- for the first time in his life.*'\n\nSam waits for the resolution. Gurov will leave his wife. Or Anna will leave her husband. Or they will be discovered. Or they will part forever. Something will *happen*.\n\nNothing happens. The final line reads: '*And it seemed as though in a little while the solution would be found, and then a new and splendid life would begin; and it was clear to both of them that they had still a long, long road before them, and that the most complicated and difficult part of it was only just beginning.*'\n\nSam stares at the page. That is not an ending. That is a refusal to end. Chekhov has spent thirty pages making us care about these two people and then he *leaves them there*, mid-sentence, mid-life, mid-problem.\n\nBut Sam realizes: that IS the honesty. Resolution would be false. Life does not resolve. The greatest love story of the nineteenth century ends with two people in a hotel room who have no idea what to do next.\n\nThe manuscript shimmers. The text fades. Sam is back in the room with the breathing bookshelves.",
