      "title": "West Briton",
      "text": "Miss Molly Ivors corners Gabriel during the lancers. She is a nationalist, firm-jawed, wearing a brooch with an Irish motto. She has read Gabriel's book reviews in *The Daily Express* -- a pro-British paper.\n\n'*Why do you write for that rag?*' she asks. Then, smiling: '*Aren't you ashamed of yourself?*'\n\nShe calls him a '*West Briton*' -- an Irishman who has turned his back on Ireland. She invites him to the Aran Isles for the summer. Gabriel, who prefers France and Belgium, stumbles through a defense: '*Irish is not my language.*' Then, sharper than he intends: '*I'm sick of my own country, sick of it!*'\n\nSam watches the exchange with fascination. This is not just a personal quarrel -- it is the Irish Question compressed into a dance. Gabriel's relationship to Ireland is ambivalent: he lives there but faces east, toward the Continent, toward culture, away from the west of Ireland where his wife Gretta grew up.\n\nJoyce wrote this story in Trieste -- an exile writing about a country he left but could never stop writing about. Sam begins to wonder whether Gabriel is Joyce's self-portrait, and whether the story is about to judge him.\n\nMiss Ivors leaves before supper. Gabriel feels relieved. He should not.",
