      "title": "Arrayed for the Bridal",
      "text": "Aunt Julia stands to sing. She is old -- grey hair, a face that looks 'like a shrivelled red apple' in the gaslight. She sings '*Arrayed for the Bridal*' and her voice, though fading, fills the room.\n\nSam listens. There is something devastating about the song choice -- a wedding song, sung by an elderly woman whose life of music and devotion to the Church is nearly over. Joyce does not underline the irony. He trusts the reader to hear it.\n\nAfter the song, the guests discuss the old Italian opera companies that used to come to Dublin. '*The old singers,*' someone says, their voices now only memories. The party is saturated with music, and every piece of music points backward -- to voices that are gone, to Dublin as it used to be, to a world that is passing.\n\nSam understands Joyce's method now. It is *accumulation* -- layering detail on detail, image on image, until meaning emerges from the sheer weight of what has been gathered. There is no plot driving forward. There is only the party, growing denser and more alive, and beneath it the slow, quiet pressure of time passing.\n\nThe party IS the story. At least, Sam thinks it is. That thought will turn out to be wrong.",
