      "text": "The party is ending. Guests are leaving. Gabriel stands at the foot of the stairs and looks up.\n\nHis wife Gretta is standing motionless on the landing, one hand on the banister, her head tilted. She is listening to something: a tenor, Bartell D'Arcy, singing '*The Lass of Aughrim*' in the room above.\n\nGabriel looks at her and thinks: '*If he were a painter he would paint her in that attitude. Distant Music he would call the picture.*'\n\nSam freezes. There it is. Gabriel is composing an *image* of his wife. He is turning a living woman into a painting, a title, an aesthetic object. He is not wondering what she is feeling. He is not asking why she has stopped. He is framing her.\n\nJoyce is setting a trap -- and Sam can see it, and Gabriel cannot. Joyce has let us share Gabriel's romanticized vision so completely that when truth arrives, the fall will be devastating.\n\nIn the cab, Gabriel is full of desire. He recalls 'moments of their secret life together, that no one knew of or would ever know of.' He is building a romantic narrative. The hotel room awaits.",
